{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778191066,"nonce":"7/4gM9xSBsiltX7ozWJf+tuGAUk=","title":"feedbax_graph_controller fails on real SimpleFeedback graphs (cycle wires not threaded by _call_single_step)","message":"Surfaced from `6fdf9a4` (first induced-gain run). When the adapter `feedbax_graph_controller` from `src/rlrmp/analysis/induced_gain.py` is invoked on a real Part 2.5 `SimpleFeedback` graph (mechanics + sensory feedback + net), `graph._call_single_step(...)` raises `KeyError: 'force'`. Root cause: cycle wires (mechanics → feedback → net) are only threaded by `_call_with_iteration`, NOT by `_call_single_step`.\n\nThe synthetic 1-component pass-through Graph used in `tests/test_induced_gain.py::test_feedbax_graph_controller_smoke` does not have a cycle, so the unit test passed even though the adapter is broken on actual usage.\n\n**Workaround currently in place** (in `scripts/run_induced_gain_part2_5.py`, commit `36aa1ad`): a private `_NetworkController` that wraps `model.nodes['net']` and reconstructs the closed loop manually, packing the feedback delay queue into the augmented hidden state. This works but is not the right long-term solution — the analyser's public API should support real `SimpleFeedback` graphs.\n\n**Two reasonable fixes:**\n1. **Extend `feedbax_graph_controller`** to thread cycle-wire `port_values` through `_call_single_step` itself, persisting them across calls in the augmented controller hidden state. Caller-transparent.\n2. **Promote the `_NetworkController` workaround to canonical** for SimpleFeedback-shaped models. Less elegant but more decoupled — wraps `model.nodes['net']` directly and reconstructs feedback wiring on the analyser side.\n\n(1) is preferable in principle (keeps the analyser using the graph's own wiring); (2) is easier and possibly more robust if the graph's cycle representation changes.\n\n**Test gap to close:** `tests/test_induced_gain.py` needs a smoke test against a graph that *has* a cycle (e.g., a minimal feedback loop: 2-component graph with a back-edge). Without that, future adapter regressions stay invisible until someone runs against a real checkpoint.","files":null}]}